# FilmDB Architecture Update — Implementation Plan

## Goal

Upgrade the FilmDB backend to use **local Parquet KB data** (built in the KB mapping step) as the primary data source, replacing external API calls where possible. Add 7 new KB-powered tools, a `FilmDBQueryEngine` data access layer, and update all orchestration modules to support new intents.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Theme Analysis Tool is deferred** — the scraping pipeline hasn't run yet, so there's no [analysis_layer](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/rag/kb_mapping.py#555-638) data. We'll define the schema but skip implementation.

---

## Current State vs. Proposed Changes

| Component | Current | Proposed |
|-----------|---------|----------|
| Data source | External APIs (TMDB, RapidAPI, Watchmode, Serper) | **Parquet KB first**, API fallback |
| Query engine | None — tools call APIs directly | New `FilmDBQueryEngine` reads from 6 parquet layers |
| Tool count | 11 API-based tools | 11 existing + **7 new KB tools** |
| Intent count | 17 | 17 existing + **4 new** (PLOT_EXPLANATION, CRITIC_SUMMARY, MOVIE_SIMILARITY, FILMOGRAPHY) |
| Routing matrix | 17 routes → API tools | 21 routes — new intents route to KB tools |
| Layout policy | 7 response modes | 7 existing + **3 new** (ANALYSIS_TEXT, FILMOGRAPHY_LIST, COMPARISON_TABLE) |
| Entity resolver | Title text → pass to API | Title text → **imdb_id lookup** via movie_entity.parquet |

---

## Proposed Changes

### RAG Query Engine

#### [NEW] [filmdb_query_engine.py](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/rag/filmdb_query_engine.py)

The central data access layer. Loads all 6 parquet files on startup, provides typed methods:

- `entity_lookup(imdb_id)` → metadata from [movie_entity](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/rag/kb_mapping.py#85-176) + [metadata_layer](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/rag/kb_mapping.py#180-218)
- `plot_analysis(imdb_id)` → text from [plot_layer](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/rag/kb_mapping.py#222-289)
- `critic_summary(imdb_id)` → aggregated reviews from [review_layer](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/rag/kb_mapping.py#293-404)
- `movie_similarity(imdb_id)` → tag-based similar movies from [recommendation_layer](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/rag/kb_mapping.py#408-499)
- [top_rated(genre?, year?, language?, count=20)](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/backend/app/services/discovery_engine_service.py#81-83) → sorted from [movie_entity](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/rag/kb_mapping.py#85-176)
- `person_filmography(person_name)` → films from IMDb [title.principals.tsv](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/kb/IMDb/title.principals.tsv/title.principals.tsv) + [title.crew.tsv](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/kb/IMDb/title.crew.tsv/title.crew.tsv)
- `compare_movies(imdb_id_a, imdb_id_b)` → combined lookup for both
- `resolve_title_to_imdb_id(title, year?)` → fuzzy match against [movie_entity](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/rag/kb_mapping.py#85-176)

**Key design decisions:**
1. Parquet files loaded once at startup via `pd.read_parquet()` — total ~235 MB in RAM
2. `resolve_title_to_imdb_id` uses pre-built `title_lower → imdb_id` dict (exact match first, then fuzzy via `rapidfuzz`)
3. For `person_filmography`: loads [title.crew.tsv](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/kb/IMDb/title.crew.tsv/title.crew.tsv) (388 MB) and [name.basics.tsv](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/kb/IMDb/name.basics.tsv/name.basics.tsv) (892 MB) — these are large files. We should build a **pre-processed person index** during the KB mapping phase instead. I will add a `person_index.parquet` layer.

> [!WARNING]
> **Person filmography** requires loading [title.crew.tsv](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/kb/IMDb/title.crew.tsv/title.crew.tsv) (12.3M rows, 388 MB) and [title.principals.tsv](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/kb/IMDb/title.principals.tsv/title.principals.tsv) (98M rows, 4.2 GB). Loading these into RAM at startup is not feasible. I propose:
> - **Option A:** Pre-build a `person_index.parquet` during KB mapping that only contains `nconst → name, profession, list of (imdb_id, role)` for people with ≥1 movie credit. This would be ~50-100 MB.
> - **Option B:** Use chunked reads from the TSV at query time (slow, ~2-5s per query).
>
> **I recommend Option A** — adds one more parquet file but keeps API response fast.

---

### KB-Powered Tool Services

All new tools go in `backend/app/services/kb/`:

#### [NEW] [kb_entity_lookup.py](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/backend/app/services/kb/kb_entity_lookup.py)
- Input: `title: str`
- Flow: `resolve_title_to_imdb_id(title)` → `entity_lookup(imdb_id)` → return metadata
- Returns: `{title, year, genres, imdb_rating, imdb_votes, overview, popularity, tmdb_id, poster_path}`
- **Falls back to existing API tools** if no KB match

#### [NEW] [kb_plot_analysis.py](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/backend/app/services/kb/kb_plot_analysis.py)
- Input: `title: str`
- Flow: `resolve → plot_analysis(imdb_id)` → return Wikipedia plot
- Returns: `{title, plot_text, source, wiki_page}`
- **Note:** Plot available for ~29.7K movies (those in Wikipedia). For unmatched, returns `not_found`.

#### [NEW] [kb_critic_summary.py](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/backend/app/services/kb/kb_critic_summary.py)
- Input: `title: str`
- Flow: `resolve → critic_summary(imdb_id)` → aggregates up to 30 reviews
- Returns: `{title, review_count, avg_sentiment, top_reviews: [{critic, text, sentiment}]}`
- **Dataset insight:** The [review_layer](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/rag/kb_mapping.py#293-404) has [sentiment](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/backend/app/services/rt_reviews_service.py#7-15) (POSITIVE/NEGATIVE/MIXED) and `is_top_critic` flags — we can prioritize top critic reviews.

#### [NEW] [kb_movie_similarity.py](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/backend/app/services/kb/kb_movie_similarity.py)
- Input: `title: str`
- Flow: `resolve → movie_similarity(imdb_id)` → tag-based matching
- Returns: `{title, recommendations: [{title, year, shared_tags, rating}]}`
- **Dataset insight:** The [recommendation_layer](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/rag/kb_mapping.py#408-499) has `ml_tags` (pipe-separated user tags like "atmospheric|plot twist|dark comedy"). We can find movies with overlapping tags AND similar `ml_avg_rating`.

#### [NEW] [kb_top_rated.py](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/backend/app/services/kb/kb_top_rated.py)
- Input: `genre?: str, year?: str, language?: str, count?: int`
- Flow: filters [movie_entity](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/rag/kb_mapping.py#85-176) by genre/year, sorts by `imdb_rating`, returns top N
- Returns: `{movies: [{title, year, rating, genres}]}`
- **Dataset insight:** The [regional_layer](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/rag/kb_mapping.py#503-551) has `language` tags — we can filter by language natively (e.g., "top rated Tamil movies" without needing an API call).

#### [NEW] [kb_person_filmography.py](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/backend/app/services/kb/kb_person_filmography.py)
- Input: `name: str`
- Flow: resolve person name → lookup `person_index.parquet` → list films
- Returns: `{name, profession, filmography: [{title, year, role, rating}]}`
- Depends on the pre-built `person_index.parquet` (see Option A above)

#### [NEW] [kb_movie_comparison.py](file:///D:/Evolve_Robot_Lab/Project/FilmDB_Demo/backend/app/services/kb/kb_movie_comparison.py)
- Input: `title_a: str, title_b: str`
- Flow: resolve both → get metadata, reviews, plot for each → structure side-by-side
- Returns: `{movie_a: {...}, movie_b: {...}}` (structured, LLM formats the narrative)

